PA 9.2 - Multiclass Classification

Our dataset consists of clinical data from patients who entered the hospital complaining of chest pain (âanginaâ) during exercise. The information collected includes:

  • age : Age of the patient

  • sex : Sex of the patient

  • cp : Chest Pain type

    • Value 0: asymptomatic
    • Value 1: typical angina
    • Value 2: atypical angina
    • Value 3: non-anginal pain

  • trtbps : resting blood pressure (in mm Hg)

  • chol : cholesterol in mg/dl fetched via BMI sensor

  • restecg : resting electrocardiographic results

    • Value 0: normal
    • Value 1: having ST-T wave abnormality (T wave inversions and/or ST elevation or depression of > 0.05 mV)
    • Value 2: showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estesâ criteria

  • thalach : maximum heart rate achieved during exercise

  • output : the doctorâs diagnosis of whether the patient is at risk for a heart attack

    • 0 = not at risk of heart attack
    • 1 = at risk of heart attack
Code

Q1: Natural Multiclass Models

Fit a multiclass KNN, Decision Tree, and LDA for the heart disease data; this time predicting the type of chest pain (categories 0 - 3) that a patient experiences. For the decision tree, plot the fitted tree, and interpret the first couple splits.

Code 
X = ha.drop("cp", axis = 1)
y = ha["cp"]

# Standardize the variables
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Split the data into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size = 0.25, random_state = 321, stratify = y)

knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
param_grid_knn = {"n_neighbors": range(1, 26)}
grid_knn = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid_knn, cv = 10, scoring = make_scorer(roc_auc_score, multi_class='ovo', average='weighted', response_method='predict_proba'))
grid_knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_knn = grid_knn.best_estimator_
best_knn.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_proba_knn = best_knn.predict_proba(X_test)
roc_auc_knn = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_knn, multi_class='ovo', average='weighted')
cv_scores_knn = cross_val_score(best_knn, X_train, y_train, cv = 10, scoring = make_scorer(roc_auc_score, multi_class='ovo', average='weighted', response_method='predict_proba'))
roc_auc_knn_cv = cv_scores_knn.mean()
best_k = grid_knn.best_params_['n_neighbors']
print("Best k Value:", best_k)
print("kNN ROC AUC Metric:", roc_auc_knn)
Best k Value: 24
kNN ROC AUC Metric: 0.637284203316812
Code 
# Plot predicted vs actual

Decision Tree ROC AUC Metric: 0.6764514320220844
Code 
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plot_tree(best_tree, filled=True, feature_names=X.columns, class_names=['0', '1', '2', '3'], max_depth=2)
plt.title("Decision Tree Visualization")
plt.show()

Interpretation

The root node (first split) separates patients based on their âthalachâ (maximum heart rate achieved during exercise). If âthalachâ is less than or equal to 145.5, it sends them down one path; otherwise, they go down another. This indicates that a patientâs maximum heart rate is the most significant factor initially in predicting chest pain type. The second level of splits further refines this by considering âageâ and âcholâ (cholesterol). For patients with âthalachâ <= 145.5, the next split is based on âageâ. For patients with âthalachâ > 145.5, the next split is based on âcholâ. This suggests that depending on their maximum heart rate, other factors like age or cholesterol become important for further differentiation of chest pain types.

Q3: OvO

Reduce your dataset to only the 0 and 1 types of chest pain.

Then, fit a Logistic Regression to predict between the two groups, and report the ROC-AUC.

Repeat comparing category 0 to 2 and 3. Which pair was the OvO approach best at distinguishing?

Code 
def train_and_evaluate_ovo(data_df, scaled_features, target_series, cat1, cat2, random_state=321):
    mask = target_series.isin([cat1, cat2])
    X_ovo = scaled_features[mask.values]
    y_ovo = target_series[mask]
    y_ovo_binary = y_ovo.apply(lambda x: 1 if x == cat2 else 0)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X_ovo, y_ovo_binary, test_size=0.25, random_state=random_state, stratify=y_ovo_binary
    )
    log_reg = LogisticRegression(random_state=random_state)
    log_reg.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_proba = log_reg.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba)
    return roc_auc

ovo_roc_auc_scores = {}

roc_auc_01 = train_and_evaluate_ovo(ha, X_scaled, ha['cp'], 0, 1)
ovo_roc_auc_scores['0 vs 1'] = roc_auc_01
print(f"ROC-AUC for cp category 0 vs 1: {roc_auc_01:.4f}")

roc_auc_02 = train_and_evaluate_ovo(ha, X_scaled, ha['cp'], 0, 2)
ovo_roc_auc_scores['0 vs 2'] = roc_auc_02
print(f"ROC-AUC for cp category 0 vs 2: {roc_auc_02:.4f}")

roc_auc_03 = train_and_evaluate_ovo(ha, X_scaled, ha['cp'], 0, 3)
ovo_roc_auc_scores['0 vs 3'] = roc_auc_03
print(f"ROC-AUC for cp category 0 vs 3: {roc_auc_03:.4f}")

best_pair = max(ovo_roc_auc_scores, key=ovo_roc_auc_scores.get)
best_score = ovo_roc_auc_scores[best_pair]
print(f"\nThe best performing OvO pair is {best_pair} with an ROC-AUC score of {best_score:.4f}")
ROC-AUC for cp category 0 vs 1: 0.7699
ROC-AUC for cp category 0 vs 2: 0.7857
ROC-AUC for cp category 0 vs 3: 0.8000

The best performing OvO pair is 0 vs 3 with an ROC-AUC score of 0.8000
